# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: selection-api
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:selection-api/api-range] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:selection-api/api-range] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:selection-api/api-range] The **`Range`** interface represents a fragment of a document that can contain nodes and parts of text nodes.
[src:selection-api/api-range] A range can be created by using the `Document.createRange()` method.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Range objects can also be retrieved by using the `getRangeAt()` method of the `Selection` object or the `caretRangeFromPoint()` method of the `Document` object.
[src:selection-api/api-range] There also is the `Range()` constructor available.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns a `Range` object with the global `Document` as its start and end.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns the deepest `Node` that contains the `startContainer` and `endContainer` nodes.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Collapses the `Range` to one of its boundary points.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Compares the boundary points of the `Range` with another `Range`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns a constant representing whether the `Node` is before, after, inside, or surrounding the range.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns -1, 0, or 1 indicating whether the point occurs before, inside, or after the `Range`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns a `DocumentFragment` copying the nodes of a `Range`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns a `Range` object with boundary points identical to the cloned `Range`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns a `DocumentFragment` created from a given string of code.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Removes the contents of a `Range` from the `Document`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Moves contents of a `Range` from the document tree into a `DocumentFragment`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns a `DOMRect` object which bounds the entire contents of the `Range`; this would be the union of all the rectangles returned by `range.getClientRects()`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns a list of `DOMRect` objects that aggregates the results of `Element.getClientRects()` for all the elements in the `Range`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns a `boolean` indicating whether the given point is in the `Range`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Insert a `Node` at the start of a `Range`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Returns a `boolean` indicating whether the given node intersects the `Range`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Sets the `Range` to contain the `Node` and its contents.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Sets the `Range` to contain the contents of a `Node`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Sets the end position of a `Range` relative to another `Node`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Sets the start position of a `Range` relative to another `Node`.
[src:selection-api/api-range] Moves content of a `Range` into a new `Node`.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] A **`Selection`** object represents the range of text selected by the user or the current position of the caret.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Each `document` is associated with a unique selection object, which can be retrieved by `document.getSelection()` or `window.getSelection()` and then be examined and modified.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] A user may make a selection from left to right (in document order) or right to left (reverse of document order).
[src:selection-api/api-selection] The ***anchor*** is where the user began the selection and the ***focus*** is where the user ends the selection.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] If you make a selection with a desktop mouse, the anchor is placed where you pressed the mouse button, and the focus is placed where you released the mouse button.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns the `Node` in which the selection begins.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Can return `null` if selection never existed in the document (e.g., an iframe that was never clicked on).
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns a number representing the offset of the selection's anchor within the `anchorNode`.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] If `anchorNode` is a text node, this is the number of characters within anchorNode preceding the anchor.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] If `anchorNode` is an element, this is the number of child nodes of the `anchorNode` preceding the anchor.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] A string describing the direction of the current selection.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns the `Node` in which the selection ends.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns a number representing the offset of the selection's focus within the `focusNode`.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] If `focusNode` is a text node, this is the number of characters within `focusNode` preceding the focus.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] If `focusNode` is an element, this is the number of child nodes of the `focusNode` preceding the focus.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns a Boolean indicating whether the selection's start and end points are at the same position.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns the number of ranges in the selection.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns a string describing the type of the current selection.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] A `Range` object that will be added to the selection.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Collapses the current selection to a single point.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Collapses the selection to the end of the last range in the selection.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Collapses the selection to the start of the first range in the selection.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Indicates if a certain node is part of the selection.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Deletes the selection's content from the document.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Removes all ranges from the selection, leaving the `anchorNode` and `focusNode` properties equal to `null` and nothing selected.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Moves the focus of the selection to a specified point.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns an array of `StaticRange` objects, each that represents a selection that might cross shadow DOM boundaries.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns a `Range` object representing one of the ranges currently selected.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Adds all the children of the specified node to the selection.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Sets the selection to be a range including all or parts of two specified DOM nodes, and any content located between them.
[src:selection-api/api-selection] Returns a string currently being represented by the selection object, i.e., the currently selected text.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In human–computer interaction, a **cursor** is an indicator used to show the current position on a computer monitor or other display device that will respond to input, such as a text cursor or a mouse pointer.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] According to Roger Bates, a young hardware designer at ARC under Bill English, the cursor on the screen was for some unknown reason also referred to as *CAT* at the time, which led to calling the new pointing device a *mouse* as well.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In most command-line interfaces or text editors, the text cursor, also known as a **caret**, is an underscore (_), a reverse block (█), or a vertical bar (|), which may be flashing or steady, indicating where text will be placed when entered (the **insertion point**).
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In text mode displays, it was not possible to show a vertical bar between characters to show where the new text would be inserted, so an underscore or block cursor was used instead.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In situations where a block was used, the block was usually created by inverting the pixels of the character using the Boolean math exclusive or function.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] On text editors and word processors of modern design on bitmapped displays, the vertical bar is typically used instead.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In a typical text editing application, the cursor can be moved by pressing various keys.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] These include the four cursor keys, the Page Up and Page Down keys, the Home key, the End key, and various key combinations involving a modifier key such as the Control key.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The position of the cursor also may be changed by moving the mouse pointer to a different location in the document and clicking.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The blinking of the text cursor is usually temporarily suspended when it is being moved; otherwise, the cursor may change position when it is not visible, making its location difficult to follow.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The concept of a blinking cursor can be attributed to Charles Kiesling Sr. via US Patent 3531796, filed in August 1967.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] Some interfaces use an underscore or thin vertical bar to indicate that the user is in insert mode, a mode where text will be inserted in the middle of the existing text, and a larger block to indicate that the user is in overtype mode, where inserted text will overwrite existing text.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In this way, a block cursor may be seen as a piece of selected text one character wide, since typing will replace the text *in* the cursor with the new text.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] A vertical line text cursor with a small left-pointing or right-pointing appendage is for indicating the direction of text flow on systems that support bi-directional text, and is thus usually known among programmers as a 'bidi cursor'.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In some cases, the cursor may split into two parts, each indicating where left-to-right and right-to-left text would be inserted.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In computing, a **pointer** or **mouse pointer** (as part of a personal computer WIMP style of interaction) is a symbol or graphical image on the computer monitor or other display device that echoes movements of the pointing device, commonly a mouse, touchpad, or stylus pen.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] It signals the point where actions of the user take place.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] It can be used in text-based or graphical user interfaces to select and move other elements.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The keyboard cursor may also be repositioned using the pointer.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] Though it is distinct from the text cursor, the mouse pointer is also being called a cursor, mouse cursor or a mouse.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The pointer commonly appears as an angled arrow (angled because historically that improved appearance on low-resolution screens), but it can vary within different programs or operating systems.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The use of a pointer is employed when the input method, or pointing device, is a device that can move fluidly across a screen and select or highlight objects on the screen.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In GUIs where the input method relies on hard keys, such as the five-way key on many mobile phones, there is no pointer employed, and instead, the GUI relies on a clear focus state.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The pointer echoes movements of the pointing device, commonly a mouse, touchpad or trackball.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] This kind of pointer is used to manipulate elements of graphical user interfaces such as menus, buttons, scrollbars or any other widget.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The pointer *hotspot* is the active pixel of the pointer, used to target a click or drag.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The standard arrow pointer has the hotspot at the tip; otherwise, it is frequently in the center, though it may reside at any location in the pointer.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In many GUIs, moving the pointer around the screen may reveal other screen hotspots as the pointer changes shape depending on the circumstances.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The I-beam pointer (also called the I-cursor) is a cursor shaped like a serifed capital letter *I*.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The purpose of this cursor is to indicate that the text beneath the cursor can be highlighted and sometimes inserted or changed.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] When pointer trails are active and the mouse or stylus is moved, the system waits a moment before removing the pointer image from the old location on the screen.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] A copy of the pointer persists at every point that the pointer has visited at that moment, resulting in a snake-like trail of pointer icons that follow the actual pointer.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] When the user stops moving the mouse or removes the stylus from the screen, the trails disappear and the pointer returns to normal.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] Pointer trails have been provided as a feature mainly for users with poor vision and for screens where low visibility may become an issue, such as LCD screens in bright sunlight.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In Windows, pointer trails may be enabled in the Control Panel, usually under the Mouse applet.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] Introduced with Windows NT, an *animated pointer* was a small looping animation that was played at the location of the pointer.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] This is used, for example, to provide a visual cue that the computer is busy with a task.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] After their introduction, many animated pointers became available for download from third party suppliers.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] Animated pointers are not without their problems.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] In addition to imposing a small additional load on the CPU, the animated pointer routines did introduce a security vulnerability.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] A client-side exploit known as the *Windows Animated Cursor Remote Code Execution Vulnerability* used a buffer overflow vulnerability to load malicious code via the animated cursor load routine of Windows.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] The idea of a cursor being used as a marker or insertion point for new data or transformations, such as rotation, can be extended to a 3D modeling environment.
[src:selection-api/cursor-user-interface] Blender, for instance, uses a 3D cursor to determine where operations such as placing meshes are to take place in the 3D viewport.
[src:selection-api/getselection] The **`getSelection()`** method of the `Window` interface returns the `Selection` object associated with the window's `document`, representing the range of text selected by the user or the current position of the caret.
[src:selection-api/getselection] A `Selection` object, or `null` if the associated document has no browsing context (for example, the window is an `<iframe>` that is not attached to a document).
[src:selection-api/getselection] When called on an `<iframe>` that is not displayed (e.g., where `display: none` is set) Firefox returns `null`, whereas other browsers returns a `Selection` object with `Selection.type` set to `None`.
[src:selection-api/selection-getrangeat] The **`getRangeAt()`** method of the `Selection` interface returns a range object representing a currently selected range.
[src:selection-api/selection-getrangeat] If the endpoints of the selected range are within a shadow tree then JavaScript does not have visibility of the shadow nodes, and the method should re-scope the range to include the host element that contains the end point.
[src:selection-api/selection-getrangeat] In practice most browsers do not yet implement this behavior, and the returned range is unpredictable.
[src:selection-api/selection-getrangeat] The zero-based index of the range to return.
[src:selection-api/selection-getrangeat] A negative number or a number greater than or equal to `Selection.rangeCount` will result in an error.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] In computing and user interface engineering, a **selection** is a list of items on which user operations will take place.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] The user typically adds items to the list manually, although the computer may create a selection automatically.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] Selections are enacted through combinations of key presses on a keyboard, with a precision pointing device (mouse or touchpad and cursor, stylus), or by hand on a touchscreen device.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] The simultaneous selection of a group of items (either a subset of elements in a list, or discontinuous regions in a text) is called a *multiple selection*.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] Context menus will usually include actions related to the objects included in the current selection – the selection provides the "context" for the menu.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] A selection method to facilitate the selection of large amounts of text or items in a long list such as files and folders in file managers is *range selection*, sparing the user from clicking or tapping each item individually.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] On desktop file managers such as the Windows Explorer and Nemo file manager, it can be used by clicking on the first item to be selected, then holding the ⇧ shift key while clicking on the last item to be selected.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] In mobile file managers, it is implemented since early versions of ES File Explorer, where only two listed items (file or directory) need to be highlighted and a button pressed to select all items in-between.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] Ideally, the two list items are navigated to with a draggable scroll bar, since it can move through long lists faster.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] The user taps or clicks on the first item, drags upward or downward, and waits for the list to scroll to the last desired item, at which the user releases the pointer or finger.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] Simultaneous editing is a technique in End-user development research to edit all items in a multiple selection.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] It allows the user to manipulate all the selected items at once through direct manipulation.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] The technique also appears in data wrangling tools, allowing the user to make the same changes to several records of the same kind in a table.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] The term *simultaneous editing* is also used to describe collaborative editing in collaborative real-time editors.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] A **column selection** is a text selection feature found in text editors which allows the user to select characters in a grid-like fashion, selecting characters in several lines at the same columns.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] This is usually initiated by pressing the alt key (instead of the shift key, which creates a continuous selection) to select text when dragging.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] Some applications also enable text to be typed in multiple lines at once using this method as a limited form of simultaneous editing.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] The Lapis text editor, Mozilla's Firefox developer tools, and the *multi edit* plugin for gedit are examples of the simultaneous editing technique that work on discontinuous regions through direct manipulation.
[src:selection-api/selection-user-interface] The Lapis editor can also create an automatic multiple selection based on an example item.
[src:selection-api/selectionchange-event] It’s been available across browsers since March 2017.
[src:selection-api/selectionchange-event] The **`selectionchange`** event of the Selection API is fired when the current `Selection` of a `Document` is changed.
[src:selection-api/selectionchange-event] This event is not cancelable and does not bubble.
[src:selection-api/selectionchange-event] The event can be handled by adding an event listener for `selectionchange` or using the `onselectionchange` event handler.
[src:selection-api/selectionchange-event] Use the event name in methods like `addEventListener()`, or set an event handler property.
